'''#NotAllMen''' is a popular [[Internet meme]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Tom|last=Ferdy |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/men/thinking-man/10924854/Is-there-a-misogynist-inside-every-man.html |title=Is there a misogynist inside every man? |website=[[Daily Telegraph]]|publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group]] |location=London, England|date=2 July 2014|accessdate=15 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=jezebel/> It is a shortened [[hashtag]] version of the phrase '''not all men are like that''',<ref>{{cite news|first=Mina|last=Malik-Hussain|url=http://www.nation.com.pk/columns/02-Jun-2014/clapping-with-both-hands|title=Clapping with Both Hands|work=[[The Nation (Pakistan)|The Nation]]||publisher=Nawa-i-Waqt Group of Publications|location=Karachi, Pakistan|date=June 2, 2014|accessdate=15 July 2014}}</ref> sometimes abbreviated '''NAMALT'''.

A [[Time magazine|''Time'' magazine]] article on the subject states that "Not all men" was previously stated as an object of frustration, but in early 2014 it became usually used as an object of mockery. Intended to counter [[generalization]]s about men’s behavior, the phrase has been criticized for deflecting conversations from uncomfortable topics, such as [[sexual assault]].<ref name="Jess Zimmerman">{{cite web|first=Jess|last=Zimmerman |url=http://time.com/79357/not-all-men-a-brief-history-of-every-dudes-favorite-argument/ |title=Not All Men: A Brief History of Every Dude's Favorite Argument |website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|publisher=[[Meredith Corporation]]|location=New York City|date=April 28, 2014|accessdate=July 15, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first1=Michel|last1=Martin|first2=Arthur|last2= Chu|url=https://www.npr.org/2014/05/30/317361633/jeopardy-champ-arthur-chu-on-nerds-entitlement-and-elliot-rodger|title=Jeopardy Champ Arthur Chu On Nerds, Entitlement And Elliot Rodger |work=[[NPR]]|date=May 30, 2014|accessdate=July 15, 2014}}</ref>

==Origin==
[[Vox (website)|Vox]] states that the phrase "not all men are like that," as a general defense of men in gendered criticisms of their behavior, has been around for more than a decade.<ref name="vox.com">{{cite web|first=Kelsey|last=McKinney|title=Here's why women have turned the "not all men" objection into a meme|url=https://www.vox.com/2014/5/15/5720332/heres-why-women-have-turned-the-not-all-men-objection-into-a-meme|accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref>{{efn|It has been used as early as 1836 in author [[Charles Dickens]]' book ''The Pickwick Papers'', in which, in response to the statement "Men are such deceivers" by Miss Wardle, Mr. Tupman replies "They are, they are, but not all men."<ref>{{cite book|first=Charles|last=Dickens|authorlink=Charles Dickens|title=The Pickwick Papers|publisher=Hueber|location=Munich, Germany|date=1905|isbn=978-1718847675|title-link=The Pickwick Papers}}</ref>}} Before 2013, "not all men" was not seen as a derailment tactic; the most common strategies cited by feminist bloggers were "'what about the men?' and 'patriarchy hurts men too'—pleas for inclusion, not for exemption".<ref name="Jess Zimmerman"/> Jasmine Bailey says the "not all men" argument "seemingly began as a sincere way to counter feminist arguments".<ref>{{cite web|first=Jasmine|last=Bailey|title=What’s up with the #YesAllWomen and #NotAllMen hashtags?|url=http://www.springfieldnewssun.com/news/news/whats-yesallwomen-and-notallmen-hashtags/nf7LF/|website=[[Springfield News-Sun]]|publisher=[[Cox Enterprises]]|location=Springfield, Ohio|date=May 25, 2014|accessdate=July 17, 2014}}</ref> #NotAllMen, however, is often impugned by [[feminists]].  The #NotAllMen [[Twitter]] hashtag was tweeted as early as 2011. The first viral tweet with this phrase, which was not yet a hashtag, was a satirical tweet by Shafiqah Hudson in February 2013: "ME: Men and boys are socially instructed to not listen to us. They are taught to interrupt us when we- RANDOM MAN: Excuse me. Not ALL men."<ref name="vox.com"/><ref>{{cite tweet|user=sassycrass|author=Shafiquah Hudson|number=304432121223716864|title=ME: Men and boys are socially instructed to not listen to us. They are taught to interrupt us when we- RANDOM MAN: Excuse me. Not ALL men.|date=20 February 2013|accessdate=18 January 2015}}</ref> The stereotypical "Not-All-Man", barging into a conversation criticizing male behavior, was caricatured in a comic by artist Matt Lubchansky on April 14, 2014.<ref name="Jess Zimmerman"/><ref name="vox.com"/><ref>{{cite web|first=Matt|last=Lubchansky|title=Save Me|website = Please Listen to Me|url=http://www.listen-tome.com/save-me/|accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref> Lubchansky’s comic was quickly retweeted and otherwise shared by several male celebrities including [[Wil Wheaton]], [[Paul F. Tompkins]], [[Matt Fraction]], and [[John Scalzi]].<ref name="Jess Zimmerman"/>

==2014 Isla Vista killings==
{{see also|2014 Isla Vista killings|YesAllWomen}}

<nowiki>#</nowiki>NotAllMen was already a [[Twitter]] [[hashtag]] created by the Twitter user Sassycrass before the [[2014 Isla Vista killings]], but it gained additional traction after the event, because of the hatred against women expressed by the shooter, [[Elliot Rodger]]. In response to the hashtag #NotAllMen, an anonymous female Twitter user created the hashtag #YesAllWomen, to express that all women are affected by sexism and [[misogyny]], even though not all men are sexist. This newly created hashtag quickly became used by women throughout social media to share their experiences of sexual discrimination and attacks.<ref>For coverage of this topic, see the following sources:
